Here's a C++ function that uses a markdown parser library (`fastmarkdown`) to convert markdown formatted text to HTML:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <fastmarkdown/parser.h>
#include <boost/=>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    FM::Parser parser;
    FM::Document document;
    FM::Element* root = parser.parseString(markdown, &document);

    // Convert the parsed document to HTML
    html.reserve(root->getContent().size());
    FM::OutputStream htmlStream(&html);
    root->accept(&FM::HtmlOutputFilter::create(&htmlStream));
    delete root;

    return html;
}
```

In this example, we use the `fastmarkdown` library to parse the markdown text and then use the `HtmlOutputFilter` to convert the parsed document to HTML. 

Please note that you'll need to install the `fastmarkdown` library and link it to your project. You can install it using vcpkg:

```bash
vcpkg install fastmarkdown:x86-windows
```

If you prefer not to use an external library, you can use a regex-based approach to perform a basic conversion, but this would likely be more limited in its capabilities. Here's a simple example:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>
#include <iostream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    // Headers
    html += "<div>";
    std::regex headerRegex("^# (.*)$", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript);
    for (std::sregex_iterator it(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), headerRegex), end; it != end; ++it) {
        std::string header = it->str();
        html += "<h" + std::to_string(header.find('#') - 1) + ">"; // Assuming 1-based header count
        html += it->str().substr(2); // Remove '#' characters
        html += "</h" + std::to_string(header.find('#') - 1) + ">\n";
    }
    html += "</div><p>";

    // Bold and Italic
    html += "<div>";
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*([^*]+\")");
    std::sreplace_if_none(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), boldRegex, "<b>$1</b>");
    std::regex italicRegex("\\*([^*]+)");
    std::sreplace_if_none(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), italicRegex, "<i>$1</i>");
    html += "</div>";

    return html;
}
```

This implementation only covers a very basic conversion for headers, bold, and italics. For a more comprehensive conversion, I recommend sticking with a markdown parser library.

